title: 2020 United States presidential election in Iowa
2020 United States presidential election in Iowa
deleted: Biden's result was an all-time best in [[Johnson County, Iowa|Johnson County]], home to [[University of Iowa]], that he won by 43 points, 1.83 percent higher than Obama in 2008; his 17-point victory in [[Story County, Iowa|Story County]], home to [[Iowa State University]], 1.2 percent up Obama's 2008 result, was a 56-year best after [[Lyndon B. Johnson]]'s 20-point victory in 1964. In [[Polk County, Iowa|Polk County]], home to state's largest city, state capital [[Des Moines, Iowa|Des Moines]], his 15-point victory, a 32-year best after Michael Dukakis' 18-point victory in 1988, was 0.75 percent higher than Obama's 2008 result and in Dallas County, he outperformed Obama's 2008 result by 3.62 points. However, in all other counties, even in more populous urban counties, he underperformed both Obama's 2008 and 2012 results. In [[Linn County, Iowa|Linn County]], home to state's second largest city, Cedar Rapids, he did 4.73% better than Hillary Clinton in 2016, but underperformed Obama's 2012 result by 4 points and in [[Scott County, Iowa|Scott County]], home to state's third largest city [[Davenport, Iowa|Davenport]], he improved Clinton's margin by 2 points, but underperformed Obama's 2008 and 2012 results by 10-11 points.
